<h2><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><a></a><strong><span style="line-height: 22px;">News</span></strong></span></h2>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">On April 14, the latest <a  href=
"http://info.rapid7.com/s0Vq0l70YNQJ0K0M4M2040T"
>Verizon 2015 Data Breach Investigations Report</a> was released.
                 The annual report confirmed some of the trends we&rsquo;ve seen emerge over the past several years, but also brought new concerns to the surface.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span lang="EN-GB">For the third year running, c</span>ompromised credentials were the most common way for attackers to breach a network.
                 Time also remains an enemy for security professionals &ndash; in 60% of breaches, attackers compromised the organization within minutes, compared to the average of 205 days it takes to discover a breach.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">In the &lsquo;due diligence&rsquo; category, we learn that reported vulnerabilities are not being patched, with 99.9% of vulnerabilities exploited more than a year after they were published.
                 Phishing is also increasing in effectiveness, with 23% of users opening phishing emails and 11% click on attachments.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">Somewhat surprisingly, the report found virtually no iOS malware for iPhones or iPads or Android malware.
                 In contrast, Verizon explained that up to 90% of malware samples are unique to a single organization, meaning signature-based anti-virus are no longer effective.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">This year's report is illuminating - yet also confirms a lot of what we already know about where security efforts should be focused this year.
  Rapid7 has solutions and services that address each of the major areas of concern.
